results.notes: Growing on fallen Magnolia acuminata cones on the edge of the “Asbury Fen”. Locally abundant. Basidiocarps becoming yellowish-brown in drying. All structures inamyloid. Clamps absent in the pileipellis and lamellar trama. Pileipellis composed of rounded cells with scattered pileocystidia. Pileocystidia smooth, hyaline and lageniform to conical. Pleurocystidia scattered; hyaline, thick-walled and fusoid-ventricose. Cheilocystidia forming a narrow band; hyaline, smooth and fusoid-ventricose to fusoid. Cheilocystidia measurements: (24.4) 26.6 – 35.3 (38.5) × (8.8) 9.2 – 11.9 (14.6) µm, Q = (2.2) 2.4 – 3.4 (4.2); N = 30, Me = 30.8 × 10.7 µm; Qe = 2.9. Spores smooth, hyaline and thin-walled. Spore measurements: (4) 4.7 – 6.9 (8.2) × (2.4) 2.7 – 3.8 (4.6) µm, Q = (1.3) 1.5 – 2 (2.2); N = 30, Me = 5.7 × 3.3 µm; Qe = 1.7

ID by Jason Hollinger
Lecanora hybocarpa + Vouauxiella lichenicola – Lecanora is C- with finely-inspersed epihymenium; the parasite has simple ~gray conidia truncate at both ends so presumably catenate ~7-11×3.5-4um, pycnidia ~60+um wide, conidiogenous cells very pale ~7-9×2.5um. This is not good or typical material of the Vouauxiella which normally just infects the margin of the host apothecia like a tiny ring of little black beads inset into the apothecia.
